commentBody:
@Barry -- Oh, thanks!  This made no sense!  

I should have said that it was lovely that the initial (first) word of all the theme CLUES is actually the "initial" word (the all-cap word that's made up of initials).  

A goof supreme, and I'm no stranger to making them!

@Francis

Hand up for having found it challenging like you, despite having gotten the gimmick. The fill tripped me up. Still, I enjoyed the solve. 
Thank you, Lance and John!

@Scott 

I believe that what Francis has sowed is puzzlement rather than discord and puzzlement surely is always worth reaping 

I would agree that discord should stay below ground  😀

@Eric Hougland

What do have against Niels Bohr?  

I was trying to determine if there was a quantum joke in there, but if there is I can't find it.

@Barry Ancona
Actually, I did not read the title, either.  
It was already too easy to see the theme/trick, so I'm glad I didn't think to do it.    That title, IMO, does not enhance the puzzle or advance the cause of entertaining construction, so Oh, Well.

@Cherry

The key is understanding that the capitalized words are just hints to the first letters of the theme answer words. They don’t relate semantically to the rest of the clue.  Semantically, the rest of the clue is what leads to the answer. Whether you like the result is up to you to decide, but as Matt said, it’s very consistent. 

I think part of the problem is that HOT, but in the first themer, seemed to suggest that the capitalized words did have something to do with the semantic cluing. HELEN OF TROY had the face that launched a thousand ships; I don’t know whether she was HOT all over.

@Bob
Right. Big difference.
Although sometimes misspellings do become mainstream. A current example that gets my goat is the common but horrible 'woah'.

@CCNY

I found it funny, too.
But it's the first time for me.

@CCNY

Love this!

And, funnily enough, when I googled the author, it turns out to be  that famous mystery writer of 20A.

@CCNY
"peas with honey" was the first thing that came to mind as I was solving that clue. In our home it was "it makes the PEAS taste funny".

@Chungclan
On today's bi-weekly zoom call with my five siblings I recalled the book of collected poems we had, and how when an elementary school teacher asked if any of us had a favorite poet I proudly answered "Yes! Anon."  (accent on the A).

@Mean Old Lady
I used to drive through that intersection every day. Lived in Midtown and worked on N. Druid Hills.
@Michelle Botwinick
My dad went to Emory and moved back to that neighborhood in retirement, so for the last 8 years of his life I drove those streets again quite often.

@gen z maddy
BRIER threw me for quite a while too. I've only ever seen BRIaR. Per Merriam-Webster, "brier" is the less-common version.

All the citations they mention use the -ar spelling, tellingly.

@JohnWM
"You know nothing, Jon Snow." 
(Says the archer on the left, frequently, in GOT.)

@Amy

Definitely a PB for me, though I'm not entirely sad about that because I had to squeeze it in around birthday celebrations for my mom. A highlight of the day was learning my nephew was one of the first to wish his Mimi a happy birthday – unprompted! 😊

Kon Mari is the name of the process developed by Marie Kondo for organizing and decluttering one's belongings. It was a big fad for a bit and continues to be popular – not to mention, she shows up in the crossword often enough! 😉

